'''Willy Johnson Semedo Afonso''' ({{IPA|pt|ˈwi.li ˈʤɔn.sɔn sɨ.ˈme.du ɐ.ˈfõ.su|lang}}<!----The player was born in France. Check for sources if his first names are pronounced in a “Portuguese way” or in a “French way”.---->; born 27 April 1994) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] for [[Cypriot First Division]] club [[AC Omonia|Omonia]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news |title=Ανακοίνωσε Σεμέδο η Ομόνοια |url=https://www.kerkida.net/eidiseis/a-katigoria/omonoia/tora-anakoinose-semedo-i-omonoia}}</ref> Born in France, Semedo plays for the [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde national team]].

==Club career==
On 31 January 2018, Semedo signed with [[R. Charleroi S.C.|Charleroi]] after a successful spell with the Cypriot club [[Alki Oroklini]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walfoot.be/fra/news/lis/2018-01-31/willy-semedo-signe-pour-2-saisons-a-charleroi|title=Officiel: Charleroi tient le remplaçant de Lukebakio|date=31 January 2018|publisher=}}</ref> He made his debut for the Belgium club in a 2–2 [[Belgian First Division A]] draw with [[K.R.C. Genk]], on 13 April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2018/04/13/belgium/pro-league/royal-charleroi-sporting-club/krc-genk/2753663/|title=Sporting Charleroi vs. Genk – 13 April 2018 – Soccerway|website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref>

On 30 August 2018, Semedo was loaned to [[Belgian First Division B]] club [[K.S.V. Roeselare|Roeselare]], for half a season, in order for him to get more playing time.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Officiel: Semedo (SC Charleroi) rejoint Roulers en prêt |trans-title=Official: Semedo (SC Charleroi) has joined Roeselare on loan |work=NordEclair |date=30 August 2018 |accessdate=15 September 2018 |url= http://www.nordeclair.be/271857/article/2018-08-30/officiel-semedo-sc-charleroi-rejoint-roulers-en-pret |language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Prêté par Charleroi, Willy Semedo fixe ses objectifs à Roulers |trans-title= |first=Malik |last=Hadrich |work=Walfoot.be |date=12 September 2018 |access-date=15 September 2018 |url= https://www.walfoot.be/fra/news/lis/2018-09-12/prete-par-charleroi-willy-semedo-fixe-ses-objectifs-a-roulers |language=}}</ref> On 1 February 2019, he moved to [[Liga I]] side [[FC Politehnica Iași (2010)|Politehnica Iași]]. Semedo subsequently signed a six-month contract with the Romanian club.<ref>[https://www.politehnicaiasi.ro/stiri/mijlocasul-francez-willy-semedo-va-semna-cu-politehnica Mijlocașul francez Willy Semedo a semnat cu Politehnica] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190202042259/https://www.politehnicaiasi.ro/stiri/mijlocasul-francez-willy-semedo-va-semna-cu-politehnica |date=2 February 2019 }}.politehnicaiasi.ro {{in lang|ro}}</ref>

In July 2019, Semedo signed for [[Ligue 2]] club [[Grenoble Foot 38|Grenoble]] on a two-year contract, where he scored 11 goals in 61 total appearances. He then moved to Cypriot club [[Pafos FC]] on a free transfer, where he totalled 20 goal contributions in 48 games.

On 28 January 2023, Semedo signed for Saudi Arabian club [[Al-Faisaly FC|Al-Faisaly]],<ref>{{cite web |title=إدارة النادي تنهي إجراءات التوقيع مع اللاعب "ويلي سيميدو " |url=https://twitter.com/AlFaisaly/status/1619333756053254145}}</ref> however, at the end of the season he returned to Cyprus, this time for 21-time domestic champions [[AC Omonia|Omonia]].<ref name=":0" /> The 2023–24 season was Semedo's best in terms of goal contributions, as he scored 14 and assisted 7 in 38 appearances in all competitions.

==International career==
Born in France, Semedo is of Cape Verdean descent. On 1 October 2020, Semedo was called by [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://criolosports.com/index.php/template/tubaroes-azuis/7396-futebol-conheca-os-novos-reforcos-dos-tubaroes-azuis-para-os-jogos-amigaveis-frente-andorra-e-guine-conacri|title=Futebol: Conheça os novos reforços dos Tubarões Azuis para os jogos amigáveis frente Andorra e Guiné Conacri|language=pt|date=1 October 2020|accessdate=5 October 2020|website=Criolo Sports|archive-date=4 December 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201204050916/http://www.criolosports.com/index.php/template/tubaroes-azuis/7396-futebol-conheca-os-novos-reforcos-dos-tubaroes-azuis-para-os-jogos-amigaveis-frente-andorra-e-guine-conacri|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made his international debut in a friendly 2–1 win over [[Andorra national football team|Andorra]] on 7 October 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/uefanationsleague/friendlies/match/2030227--andorra-vs-cape-verde-islands/|title=Andorra-Cabo Verde LIVE &#124; UEFA Nations League|website=[[UEFA]]}}</ref>

Since then, Semedo has featured for Cape Verde in the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]], the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification|2022]] and [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification|2026 World Cup qualifiers]], as well as the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]], where he helped Cape Verde reach the quarter-finals, equalling the team's best performance in the tournament.{{Citation needed|date=October 2025}}

